SIMPLE: federal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Federal
<hw>Fed"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>foedus</ets> league, treaty, compact; akin to <ets>fides</ets>
faith: cf. F. <ets>f⟦eacute⟧d⟦eacute⟧ral</ets>. see
<er>Faith</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to a league or
treaty; derived from an agreement or covenant between parties,
especially between nations; constituted by a compact between parties,
usually governments or their representatives.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Romans compelled them, contrary to all <qex>federal</qex>
right, . . . to part with Sardinia.</q> <rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Composed
of states or districts which retain only a subordinate and limited
sovereignty, as the <xex>Union</xex> of the United States, or the
<xex>Sonderbund</xex> of Switzerland.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Consisting
or pertaining to such a government; <as>as, the <ex>Federal</ex>
Constitution; a <ex>Federal</ex> officer</as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>Friendly or devoted to such a government; <as>as, the
<ex>Federal</ex> party</as>. see <er>Federalist</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Federal Congress</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Congress</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Federal</ent>⟦br⟧

